[Category:English male comedians]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male voice actors]]\n[[Category:English podcasters]]\n[[Category:British men podcasters]]\n[[Category:English political commentators]]\n[[Category:English television personalities]]\n[[Category:English television producers]]\n[[Category:Late night television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:National Youth Theatre members]]\n[[Category:People educated at Mark Rutherford School]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Writers Guild of America Award winners]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n[[Category:American television personalities]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{distinguish|text=[[John Olver]]}}\n{{pp-pc1|expiry=indef}}\n{{short description|English comedian and television host}}\n{{Use British English Oxford spelling|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name                = John Oliver\n| image               = John Oliver November 2016.jpg\n| caption             = Oliver in November 2016\n| birth_name          = John William Oliver\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1977|4|23}}\n| birth_place         = [[Erdington]], [[Birmingham]], England\n| nationality         = {{Plainlist|\n* British (1977\u2013present)\n* American (2019\u2013present)\n}}\n| education           = [[Mark Rutherford School]]\n| alma_mater          = [[Christ's College, Cambridge]]\n| medium              = {{hlist|Stand-up|television|film|books}}\n| active              = 1998\u2013present\n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Political satire|Political]]/[[news satire]]|[[observational comedy]]|[[black comedy]]|[[sarcasm]]|[[cringe comedy]]|[[self-deprecation]]}}\n| subject             = {{hlist|[[Politics of the United States|American politics]]|[[Culture of England|British culture]]|[[Pundit (expert)|political punditry]]|[[popular culture]]|[[News|current events]]|[[Media (communication)|mass media/news media]]|[[civil rights]]}}\n| spouse              = {{marriage|Kate Norley|October 2011}}\n| children            = 2\n| signature           =\n| website             = {{URL|{{#property:P856}}}}\n}}\n'''John William Oliver''' (born 23 April 1977)<ref name=biography.com>{{cite web | url = http://www.biography.com/people/john-oliver-21284225 | title = John Oliver Biography: Political Scientist, Radio Personality, Actor, Comedian, Writer, Television Personality (1977\u2013) | publisher = Biography.com ([[FYI (U.S. TV network)|FYI]] / [[A&E Networks]]) | access-date = 12 November 2015 | archivedate = 7 November 2015 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151107171718/http://www.biography.com/people/john-oliver-21284225 | url-status = dead }}</ref><!--Biography.com cite also verifies full name John William Oliver--> is an English-American<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/watch-america-john-oliver-is-officially-a-us-citizen-now-1273984?|title=Watch Out, America: John Oliver Is Officially a U.S. Citizen Now|last=Guthrie|first=Marisa|newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=29 January 2020|accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref> comedian, writer, producer, political commentator, actor, and television host. Oliver started his career as a stand-up comedian, both in the United Kingdom and United States. He came to wider attention for his work on ''[[The Daily Show|The Daily Show with Jon Stewart]]'' as its senior British correspondent from 2006 to 2013. Oliver won three [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s for his work as a writer on ''The Daily Show'' and was its [[guest host]] for an eight-week period in 2013. In addition to ''The Daily Show'', Oliver co-hosted the satirical comedy [[podcast]] ''[[The Bugle]]'' (2007\u20132015) with [[Andy Zaltzman]], with whom Oliver had previously co-hosted the radio series ''[[Political Animal (radio show)|Political Animal]]'', and hosted ''[[John Oliver's New York Stand-Up Show]]'' on [[Comedy Central]] from 2010 to 2013. He has also acted on television, most notably in a recurring role as Ian Duncan on the [[NBC]] [[Situation comedy|sitcom]] ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'', and in films, notably [[voice acting|voice-over work]] in ''[[The Smurfs (film)|The Smurfs]]'' (2011) and its [[The Smurfs 2|sequel]], and the [[The Lion King (2019 film)|remake of ''The Lion King'']].\n\nSince 2014, Oliver has been the host of the [[HBO]] series ''[[Last Week Tonight with John Oliver]]''. He has received widespread critical and popular recognition for his work on the series, whose influence over US culture, legislation, and policymaking has been dubbed the \"John Oliver effect\".<ref name=\"time.com\">{{cite news |last1=Luckerson |first1=Victor |title=How the 'John Oliver Effect' Is Having a Real-Life Impact |url=http://time.com/3674807/john-oliver-net-neutrality-civil-forfeiture-miss-america/ |website=[[TIME.com|TIME]] |ISSN=0040-781X |OCLC=1311479|access-date=28 August 2015|date=20 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150810231912/http://time.com/3674807/john-oliver-net-neutrality-civil-forfeiture-miss-america/|archive-date=10 August 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Dekel\">{{cite web |first=Jon |last=Dekel |title=The John Oliver effect: How the Daily Show alum became the most trusted man in America|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/arts/television/the-john-oliver-effect-how-the-daily-show-alum-became-the-most-trusted-man-in-america|website=National Post|issn=1486-8008|access-date=27 August 2015|date=18 February 2015|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20180727192525/https://nationalpost.com/entertainment/television/the-john-oliver-effect-how-the-daily-show-alum-became-the-most-trusted-man-in-america|archive-date=27 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> For his work on ''Last Week Tonight'', Oliver has won eight [[Emmy Award]]s and two [[Peabody Award]]s and was included in the 2015 ''[[Time 100|Time]]'' [[Time 100|100]], being described as a \"comedic agent of change...powerful because he isn't afraid to tackle important issues thoughtfully, without fear or apology.\"<ref name=vanf1 /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://time.com/collection-post/3822865/john-oliver-2015-time-100/ |title=Elizabeth Biernan \u2013 John Oliver, The 100 Most Influential People |work=Time |access-date=4 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171128121134/http://time.com/collection-post/3822865/john-oliver-2015-time-100/ |archive-date=28 November 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Many have opined that Oliver's work is [[journalism]] or [[investigative journalism]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/17/business/media/john-olivers-complicated-fun-connects-for-hbo.html |title=John Oliver's Complicated Fun Connects for HBO|date=16 November 2014|accessdate=30 April 2015|last=Carr|first=David|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://time.com/3589285/unfortunately-john-oliver-you-are-a-journalist/ |title=Unfortunately, John Oliver, You Are a Journalist|last=Poniewozik|first=James|date=17 November 2014|accessdate=30 April 2015|work=Time}}</ref> a claim Oliver himself<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/last-week-tonight-does-real-journalism-no-matter-what-john-oliver-says|title='Last Week Tonight' Does Real Journalism, No Matter What John Oliver Says|last=Suebsaeng|first=Asawin|newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=29 September 2014|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref> and other journalists dispute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.americamagazine.org/arts-culture/2017/02/10/please-stop-watching-john-oliver|title=Please stop watching John Oliver|last=Davis|first=Zac|date=February 10, 2017|website=America Magazine|language=en|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsandtimes.com/2016/08/editorial-john-oliver-is-not-a-journalist/|title=Editorial: John Oliver is Not a Journalist|last=Staff|date=2016-08-15|website=News and Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nOliver was born on 23 April 1977 in [[Erdington|Erdington, Birmingham, West Midlands]], England,<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite news | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/comedy/features/made-in-manhattan-john-oliver-on-taking-satire-stateside-1937408.html | title = Made in Manhattan: John Oliver on taking satire stateside | first = David | last = Usborne | date = 7 April 2010 | work = [[The Independent]] | location = UK | access-date = 1 September 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161128053659/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/comedy/features/made-in-manhattan-john-oliver-on-taking-satire-stateside-1937408.html | archive-date = 28 November 2016 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> to Carole and Jim Oliver. His father was both a school headmaster and social worker, and his mother was a music teacher. Both of his parents are originally from [[Liverpool|Liverpool, Merseyside]]. His uncle was the composer [[Stephen Oliver (composer)|Stephen Oliver]], and [[William Boyd Carpenter]] was a paternal great-great-grandfather, [[Bishop of Ripon (modern diocese)|Bishop of Ripon]] and court chaplain to [[Queen Victoria]].<ref name=vanf1 /><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/51267|title=Oliver, Stephen Michael Harding (1950\u20131992), composer|journal=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|access-date=4 September 2015|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/51267|year=2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118072856/http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/51267|archive-date=18 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince childhood, he has been a fan of [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool FC]], noting in interviews that \"my mum's family are from [[Knotty Ash]] and my dad's family are from [[Wirral Peninsula|the Wirral]], so supporting Liverpool was very much not a choice\".<ref>{{cite news|title=My dad told me, always remember Istanbul|url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/2016-tour/228210-my-dad-told-me-always-remember-istanbul|publisher=LiverpoolFC.com|date=27 July 2016|access-date=26 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160724200100/http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/2016-tour/228210-my-dad-told-me-always-remember-istanbul|archive-date=24 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> As a child, Oliver was educated in [[Bedford]] at the [[Mark Rutherford School]].<ref name=vanf1>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/01/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-facts|title=John Oliver Is Horrified by Massages and Is a \"Committed Coward\": What You Should Know About the Host of *Last Week Tonight*|first=David|last=Kamp|magazine=Vanity Fair|access-date=4 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905122244/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/01/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-facts|archive-date=5 September 2015|url-status=live|ISSN=0733-8899}}</ref><ref name=guardianinterview>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/jul/23/mondaymediasection.broadcasting4 | title=Interview with John Oliver | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=23 July 2007 | access-date=21 April 2009 | location=London | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002180426/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/jul/23/mondaymediasection.broadcasting4 | archive-date=2 October 2013 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://tellyspotting.org/2011/03/07/10-minutes-with-john-oliver-a-tellyspotting-brush-with-british-greatness/ |title = Ten Minutes with John Oliver |first = Bill |last = Young |website = Tellyspotting.org |date = 7 March 2011 |access-date = 7 July 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140116140341/http://tellyspotting.org/2011/03/07/10-minutes-with-john-oliver-a-tellyspotting-brush-with-british-greatness/ |archive-date = 16 January 2014 |url-status = dead |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFollowing secondary school, he studied at [[Christ's College, Cambridge]]. While a student there in the mid-to-late 1990s, Oliver was a member of the [[Footlights|Cambridge Footlights]], the university theatrical club run by students of [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge University]]. Oliver's contemporaries in the troupe included [[David Mitchell (comedian)|David Mitchell]] and [[Richard Ayoade]]. In 1997, he became the club's vice president.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cambridge Footlights Alumni, 1990\u20131999 |url=http://www.footlights.org/alumni-archive?name=1990-1999 |publisher=Cambridge Footlights |access-date=6 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102122535/http://www.footlights.org/alumni-archive?name=1990-1999 |archivedate=2 November 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Freeman|first=Hadley|title=David Mitchell: goodbye lonely nerd|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/oct/19/david-mitchell-victoria-coren-engagement|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 August 2013|date=19 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108004404/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/oct/19/david-mitchell-victoria-coren-engagement|archive-date=8 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1998, Oliver graduated from Christ's College with a degree in English.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |url=http://www.admin.cam.ac.uk/reporter/1997-8/weekly/5744/5.html |title=Reporter 8/7/98: Congregations of the Regent House on 26 and 27 June 1998 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Reporter]] |access-date=23 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103230652/http://www.admin.cam.ac.uk/reporter/1997-8/weekly/5744/5.html |archive-date=3 January 2010 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Oliver's Twist on These 'Terrifying Times'|url=http://tech.mit.edu/V128/N21/johnoliver.html|work=The Tech|publisher=MIT|access-date=1 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521150941/http://tech.mit.edu/V128/N21/johnoliver.html|archive-date=21 May 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Stand-up===\n[[File:Wyatt Cenac, John Oliver and Rory Albanese at Moravian College.jpg|thumb|[[Wyatt Cenac]], John Oliver, and [[Rory Albanese]] after performing comedy at [[Moravian College]] in [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]] in April 2009]]\n\nOliver first appeared at the [[Edinburgh Fringe|Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] in [[2001 Edinburgh Festival Fringe|2001]] as part of ''The Comedy Zone'', a late-night showcase of newer acts, where he played the character of an \"oleaginous journalist\".<ref name=splitsider>{{cite web|last=Czajkowski|first=Elise|title=A Look Back at John Oliver's Pre-'Daily Show' Work|url=http://splitsider.com/2013/07/a-look-back-at-john-olivers-pre-daily-show-work/|publisher=Splitsider.com|access-date=26 July 2013|date=22 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727183935/http://splitsider.com/2013/07/a-look-back-at-john-olivers-pre-daily-show-work/|archive-date=27 July 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> At the Festival and similar venues, Oliver frequently worked with other members of the Chocolate Milk Gang, a group of comedians who often collaborated and performed with one another, including [[Daniel Kitson]], [[Russell Howard]], [[David O'Doherty|David O\u2019Doherty]], and [[Alun Cochrane]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/john-oliver-dominic-maxwell-london-times/|title=The John Oliver Origins Story|access-date=25 June 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625194243/https://www.adweek.com/digital/john-oliver-dominic-maxwell-london-times/|archive-date=25 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.list.co.uk/article/5314-russell-howard/|title=Russell Howard|date=17 October 2007|work=The List|access-date=25 June 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625185522/https://www.list.co.uk/article/5314-russell-howard/|archive-date=25 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08b131h|title=26/01/2017, Afternoon Edition \u2013 BBC Radio 5 live|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=25 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420133438/https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08b131h|archive-date=20 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He performed his debut solo show in [[2002 Edinburgh Festival Fringe|2002]] and returned in [[2003 Edinburgh Festival Fringe|2003]]. In [[2004 Edinburgh Festival Fringe|2004]] and [[2005 Edinburgh Festival Fringe|2005]], he collaborated with [[Andy Zaltzman]] on a [[double act]] and co-hosting ''[[Political Animal (radio)|Political Animal]]'', with various acts performing political material.\n\nAfter moving to New York City for ''[[The Daily Show]]'', Oliver began performing stand-up in small clubs around the city and later headlined shows in larger venues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newyork.timeout.com/articles/comedy/2529/oliver-twisted|title=Oliver twisted&nbsp;\u2013 Time Out New York Issue 593|date=8 February 2007|access-date=21 April 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090725065322/http://newyork.timeout.com/articles/comedy/2529/oliver-twisted|archive-date=25 July 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> Oliver's first stand-up special, titled ''John Oliver: Terrifying Times'', debuted on [[Comedy Central]] in 2008 and was later released on DVD.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://blogcritics.org/dvd-review-john-oliver-terrifying-times/ | title=John Oliver: Terrifying Times Review | work=Blogcritics | date=25 August 2008 | access-date=10 January 2016 | last=Stanislawski | first=Ethan | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115040758/http://blogcritics.org/dvd-review-john-oliver-terrifying-times/ | archivedate=15 January 2016 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Since 2010, Oliver has hosted four seasons of ''[[John Oliver's New York Stand-Up Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=John Oliver's New York Stand-Up Show |url=http://www.cc.com/shows/john-oliver-s-new-york-stand-up-show |publisher=Comedy Central |access-date=19 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903065414/http://www.cc.com/shows/john-oliver-s-new-york-stand-up-show |archive-date=3 September 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref> In 2013, he went to Afghanistan on a USO tour to perform stand-up for the troops there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/3689337/watch-john-oliver-troops/|title=Watch John Oliver Explain Why He Tased Himself for the Troops|website=Time|language=en|access-date=25 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420133437/http://time.com/3689337/watch-john-oliver-troops/|archive-date=20 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wptv.com/newsy/john-olivers-shocking-display-for-us-troops|title=John Oliver's Shocking Display For U.S. Troops|last=Sargent|first=Jay Strubberg , Mikah|date=30 January 2015|work=WPTV|access-date=25 June 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625050451/https://www.wptv.com/newsy/john-olivers-shocking-display-for-us-troops|archive-date=25 June 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Transitcentermanas-No Longer Updated-|title=Oliver and Company|date=23 August 2013|url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=5adW3lol3NE|access-date=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Edward Helmore in ''[[The Guardian]]'', \"His style leans toward the kind that Americans like best from the British \u2013 exaggerated, full of odd accents and mannerisms, in the vein of [[Monty Python]].\"<ref name=guardianinterview /> Oliver has used his British culture as a primary subject of his jokes.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Oliver \u2013 Ancestral Idiocy|url=https://www.cc.com/video-clips/r0726r/john-oliver-s-new-york-stand-up-show-ancestral-idiocy|website=Comedy Central|access-date=1 April 2016|date=13 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331043259/http://www.cc.com/video-clips/r0726r/john-oliver-s-new-york-stand-up-show-ancestral-idiocy|archive-date=31 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome Back To Morass \u2013 News of the world Schadenfreudegasm|url=http://www.cc.com/video-clips/0d5jm5/the-daily-show-with-jon-stewart-welcome-back-to-morass---news-of-the-world-schadenfreudegasm|website=Comedy Central|access-date=1 April 2016|date=11 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415105946/http://www.cc.com/video-clips/0d5jm5/the-daily-show-with-jon-stewart-welcome-back-to-morass---news-of-the-world-schadenfreudegasm|archive-date=15 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Oliver describes his own accent as a \"mongrel\" of [[Brummie#Accent|Brummie]], [[Scouse]], and [[English in southern England#Bedfordshire|Bedford]] influences.<ref>{{cite web|last=Marsh|first=Steve|title=John Oliver on Hosting The Daily Show and Being Less of a Mean Brit While Doing So|url=http://www.vulture.com/2013/06/john-oliver-the-daily-show-interview.html|publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] blog Vulture.com|access-date=23 August 2013|date=7 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130905042708/http://www.vulture.com/2013/06/john-oliver-the-daily-show-interview.html|archive-date=5 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOliver continues to perform stand up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://iamjohnoliver.com/live.html|title=John Oliver \u2013 Official Site|website=iamjohnoliver.com|language=en|access-date=25 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702211823/http://iamjohnoliver.com/live.html|archive-date=2 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===''Mock the Week''===\nPrior to joining ''The Daily Show'', Oliver was making appearances on British television as a panellist on the satirical news quiz ''[[Mock the Week]]''.<ref name=splitsider /> He was a frequent guest on the [[List of Mock the Week episodes|first two series]] in 2005 and 2006, appearing in 7 out of 11 episodes.<ref name=splitsider />\n\n===''The Daily Show with Jon Stewart''===\n[[File:John Oliver Wyatt Cenac hug Shankbone.jpg|thumb|Oliver and [[Wyatt Cenac]] at the launch of ''[[Earth (The Book)|Earth]]'']]\n\nOliver joined ''[[The Daily Show with Jon Stewart]]'' as its Senior British Correspondent in July 2006. He says he was interviewed for the show on the recommendation of comedian [[Ricky Gervais]], who had never met Oliver, but was familiar with his work.<ref>{{cite news|last=Usborne|first=David|title=Made in Manhattan: John Oliver on taking satire stateside|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/comedy/features/made-in-manhattan-john-oliver-on-taking-satire-stateside-1937408.html|work=The Independent|access-date=20 June 2013|date=7 April 2010|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128053659/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/comedy/features/made-in-manhattan-john-oliver-on-taking-satire-stateside-1937408.html|archive-date=28 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> It was his first time in the United States. Two weeks after the interview, he got the job, flying from London to New York on a Sunday and unexpectedly appearing on camera the next day.<ref name=\"thrhbo\">{{cite news|last=Guthrie|first=Marisa|title=John Oliver on the Luxurious 'Freedom' of HBO, His Complicated Relationship With NYC|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-luxurious-freedom-hbo-696165|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=19 April 2014|date=16 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418232827/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-luxurious-freedom-hbo-696165|archive-date=18 April 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Carter|first=Bill|title=Now Nattering on His Own Throne|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/27/arts/television/john-oliver-launches-last-week-tonight-on-hbo.html|work=The New York Times|access-date=24 April 2014|date=23 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424124445/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/27/arts/television/john-oliver-launches-last-week-tonight-on-hbo.html|archive-date=24 April 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Oliver received [[Emmy Award]]s for outstanding writing in 2009, 2011, and 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Primetime Emmy Award Database |url=http://www.emmys.com/award_history_search?person=%22John+Oliver%22 |publisher=Academy of Television Arts & Sciences |access-date=20 June 2013 }}{{deadurl|fix-attempted|date=January 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring the summer of 2013, Oliver [[guest host|guest-hosted]] ''The Daily Show'' for eight weeks while Stewart directed his film ''[[Rosewater (film)|Rosewater]]''.<ref name=guesthost>{{cite web|last=Fleming|first=Mike Jr.|title=Update: Jon Stewart Taking Summer 'Daily Show' Hiatus To Direct First Film And \"Challenge\" Himself, John Oliver To Sub|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/03/jon-stewart-daily-show-hiatus-john-oliver-hosting-rosewater/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=16 August 2013|date=5 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130807021758/http://www.deadline.com/2013/03/jon-stewart-daily-show-hiatus-john-oliver-hosting-rosewater/|archive-date=7 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Oliver's performance received positive reviews,<ref>{{cite web|last=Paskin|first=Willa|title=Jon Stewart who?: John Oliver's \"Daily Show\" is almost too good|url=http://www.salon.com/2013/06/14/john_oliver_on_the_daily_show_is_almost_too_good/|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|access-date=16 August 2013|date=14 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130816042946/http://www.salon.com/2013/06/14/john_oliver_on_the_daily_show_is_almost_too_good/|archive-date=16 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Grant|first=Drew|title=The Daily Show Down: Why John Oliver Is the Best Thing to Happen to Late Night Since Colbert|url=http://observer.com/2013/06/the-daily-showdown-why-john-oliver-is-the-best-thing-to-happen-to-late-night-since-colbert-video/|work=[[New York Observer]]|access-date=16 August 2013|date=28 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130724040421/http://observer.com/2013/06/the-daily-showdown-why-john-oliver-is-the-best-thing-to-happen-to-late-night-since-colbert-video/|archive-date=24 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Carlson|first=Erin|title='Daily Show': John Oliver Makes Hilarious Debut as Host|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/daily-show-john-oliver-makes-566167|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=16 August 2013|date=11 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130617220005/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/daily-show-john-oliver-makes-566167|archive-date=17 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Molloy|first=Tim|title=Review: John Oliver's 'Daily Show' Is Sharp as Ever|url=http://www.thewrap.com/tv/article/review-john-olivers-daily-show-sharp-ever-96536|website=TheWrap.com|access-date=16 August 2013|date=10 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130808183630/http://www.thewrap.com/tv/article/review-john-olivers-daily-show-sharp-ever-96536|archive-date=8 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> with some critics suggesting that he should eventually succeed Stewart as host of ''The Daily Show'' or receive his own show.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fox|first=Jesse David|title=We Can Now Consider John Oliver The Daily Show's Heir Apparent|url=http://www.vulture.com/2013/08/john-oliver-the-daily-shows-heir-apparent.html|work=Vulture|access-date=16 August 2013|date=15 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130817053456/http://www.vulture.com/2013/08/john-oliver-the-daily-shows-heir-apparent.html|archive-date=17 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Busis|first=Hillary|title=John Oliver bids farewell to 'Daily Show' hosting gig \u2013 how'd he do?|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2013/08/16/john-oliver-daily-show-last-day/|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=16 August 2013|date=16 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130816162624/http://popwatch.ew.com/2013/08/16/john-oliver-daily-show-last-day/|archive-date=16 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Holpuch|first=Amanda|title=John Oliver hosts The Daily Show without Jon Stewart \u2013 triumphantly|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/us-news-blog/2013/jun/11/john-oliver-daily-show-jon-stewart|work=The Guardian|access-date=16 August 2013|date=11 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812223146/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/us-news-blog/2013/jun/11/john-oliver-daily-show-jon-stewart|archive-date=12 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> CBS discussed the possibility of Oliver replacing [[Craig Ferguson]] on ''[[The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson|The Late Late Show]]''.<ref name=\"thrhbo\" /> Three months after his ''Daily Show'' hosting, HBO announced it was giving Oliver his own late-night show.<ref name=HBO>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title='Daily Show's John Oliver To Host Weekly Comedy Talk Show For HBO|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/11/john-oliver-to-host-weekly-comedy-talk-show-for-hbo/|website=Deadline Hollywood|access-date=20 December 2013|date=14 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220192006/http://www.deadline.com/2013/11/john-oliver-to-host-weekly-comedy-talk-show-for-hbo/|archive-date=20 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===''The Bugle''===\nFrom October 2007 to May 2015, Oliver co-hosted ''[[The Bugle]]'', a weekly satirical comedy [[podcast]], with [[Andy Zaltzman]]. Originally produced by ''[[The Times]]'' of London, it became an independent project in 2012. Its 200th episode aired on 13 July 2012.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/audio_video/podcasts/the_bugle/ | title=The Bugle&nbsp;\u2013 Audio Newspaper for a Visual World | work=The Times | location=London | access-date=7 May 2010 | first1=Sam | last1=Coates | first2=Francis | last2=Elliott | first3=Roland | last3=Watson | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509182622/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/audio_video/podcasts/the_bugle/ | archive-date=9 May 2008 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The show reached a download count of 500,000 times a month.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|title='Last Week Tonight With John Oliver' Debuts April 27 on HBO|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/04/24/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-debuts-april-27-on-hbo/257243/|work=TVbytheNumbers|publisher=zap2it|access-date=25 April 2014|date=24 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425060739/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/04/24/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver-debuts-april-27-on-hbo/257243/|archive-date=25 April 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===''John Oliver's New York Stand-Up Show''===\nIn 2009, Comedy Central announced that it would be ordering six episodes of the Oliver hosted ''[[John Oliver's New York Stand-Up Show]]'', a stand-up series on Comedy Central that featured sets from himself and other stand-up comedians, including [[Janeane Garofalo]], [[Brian Posehn]], [[Paul F. Tompkins]] and [[Marc Maron]].<ref name=\"Hibberd\">{{cite journal |last1=Hibberd |first1=James |title=Comedy extends an Oliver branch |journal=Hollywood Reporter |date=19 November 2009 |volume=412 |issue=19 |page=11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2009/11/comedy-central-gives-john-oliver-his-own-stand-up-comedy-series.html|title=Comedy Central gives John Oliver his own standup comedy series|work=Los Angeles Times|date=18 November 2009|access-date=19 November 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091122200121/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2009/11/comedy-central-gives-john-oliver-his-own-stand-up-comedy-series.html|archive-date=22 November 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> Oliver executively produced the show along with Avalon Television's Richard Allen-Turner, David Martin, James Taylor and [[Jon Thoday]].<ref name=\"Hibberd\"/> Each episode featured four comics.<ref name=\"Hibberd\"/> From 2010 to 2013, four seasons of the show were produced, the final lasting eight episodes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/john-olivers-new-york-stand-up-show/episodes/299769|title=John Oliver's New York Stand-Up Show {{!}} TV Guide|website=TVGuide.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-28}}</ref>\n\n===''Last Week Tonight''===\n{{Main|Last Week Tonight with John Oliver}}\nOliver began hosting ''[[Last Week Tonight with John Oliver]]'', a [[late-night talk show]] that takes a satirical look at news, politics, and current events, on 27 April 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Patten|first=Dominic|title=HBO Sets Name & Date For John Oliver Debut|url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/02/hbo-sets-name-date-for-john-oliver-debut/|access-date=12 February 2014|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=12 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140214111313/http://www.deadline.com/2014/02/hbo-sets-name-date-for-john-oliver-debut/|archive-date=14 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> His initial two-year contract with HBO was extended through 2017 in February 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/john-oliver-will-stay-on-hbo-through-2017-1201435357/|title=John Oliver Will Stay at HBO Through 2017|first=Brian|last=Steinberg|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=17 February 2015|access-date=17 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170309160627/http://variety.com/2015/tv/news/john-oliver-will-stay-on-hbo-through-2017-1201435357/|archive-date=9 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3712367/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-renewed/|title=Last Week Tonight With John Oliver Gets 2 More Seasons|first=Victor|last=Luckerson|website=TIME.com|date=17 February 2015|access-date=17 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923003722/http://time.com/3712367/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-renewed/|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and through 2020 in September 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/12/arts/television/john-oliver-hbo-contract.html |title=John Oliver Extends HBO Contract Through 2020 |last=Koblin |first=John |work=The New York Times |date=12 September 2017 |accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref> Oliver says he has full creative freedom, including free rein to criticize corporations, given HBO's ad-free subscription model.<ref name=\"thrhbo\" /> His work on the show led to Oliver being named on the list of [[Time (magazine)|''Time'' magazine's]] [[Time 100|\"100 Most Influential People\"]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://time.com/3822865/john-oliver-2015-time-100/ |title=John Oliver |first=Elizabeth |last=Bierman |series=Time 100 |work=Time.com |date=15 April 2015 |access-date=18 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419170530/http://time.com/3822865/john-oliver-2015-time-100/ |archive-date=19 April 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, ''Last Week Tonight'' was honoured with a [[Peabody Award]] in the \"Entertainment\" category for \"bringing satire and journalism even closer together,\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver|title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO)|website=The Peabody Awards|access-date=18 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121416/http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/last-week-tonight-with-john-oliver|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> at the 77th Annual Peabody Awards.\n\n===Television acting===\nAs a boy, Oliver played Felix Pardiggle, a minor role in the [[BBC]] drama ''[[Bleak House (1985 TV serial)|Bleak House]]'' in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|title='Daily Show' star John Oliver heads to Irvine|url=http://www.ocregister.com/soundcheck/oliver-481457-comedy-irvine.html|work=Orange County Register|access-date=24 August 2013|date=23 November 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031001241/http://www.ocregister.com/soundcheck/oliver-481457-comedy-irvine.html|archive-date=31 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOliver had a recurring role on the [[NBC]] comedy ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'' as psychology professor Ian Duncan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://watching-tv.ew.com/2009/05/nbc-new-fall-sh.html|title=Rating NBC's new fall shows: 'Parenthood,' a 'Trauma,' a 'Community,' '100 Questions,' and oh 'Mercy'!|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=4 May 2009|access-date=4 May 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090507183736/http://watching-tv.ew.com/2009/05/nbc-new-fall-sh.html|archive-date=7 May 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> However, he declined becoming a regular cast member of the series because he did not want to leave ''The Daily Show'' for it. He did not appear in the show's third and fourth seasons, but returned in season five, appearing in seven of its 13 episodes. He was not in season six which aired on [[Yahoo!]]<ref>Ryan, Patrick (31 December 2013). [http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/24680606-421/john-oliver-resumes-his-community-tenure.html \"John Oliver Resumes his ''Community'' Tenure.\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104030216/http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/24680606-421/john-oliver-resumes-his-community-tenure.html |date=4 January 2014 }} Chicago Sun Times (''SunTimes.com''). Retrieved 16 January 2014.</ref><ref>Ryan, Patrick (10 December 2013). [https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2013/12/09/john-oliver-returns-to-community/3871517/ \"Sneak Peek: John Oliver Returns to 'Community'.\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104224601/http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2013/12/09/john-oliver-returns-to-community/3871517/ |date=4 November 2016 }} ''USA Today''. Retrieved 16 January 2014.</ref>\n\nOliver has also worked on ''[[Gravity Falls]]'' as the voice of Sherlock Holmes (season 1, episode 3), ''[[Rick and Morty]]'' as an amoeba named Dr. Xenon Bloom (season 1, episode 3), ''[[People Like Us (mockumentary)|People Like Us]]'' as a bank manager (season 2, episode 5), ''[[Randy Cunningham: 9th Grade Ninja]]'' as the voice of Coach Green (season 1, episode 9), ''[[My Hero (UK TV series)|My Hero]]'' as a man from the BBC (season 2, episode 5), ''[[Green Wing]]'' as a car salesman (season 1, episode 1), and ''[[Bob's Burgers]]'' as a cat agent (season 7, episode 10).\n\nOliver guest starred as Booth Wilkes-John<!-- \"Booth Wilkes-John\" is the accurate name of the cartoon character (not the historical figure); do not edit before reading the citation --><ref name=bwj>{{cite web|last1=Perkins|first1=Dennis|title=The Simpsons: \"Pay Pal\"|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/simpsons-pay-pal-204525|website=The A.V. Club|access-date=7 September 2015|date=11 May 2014|quote=As the Simpsons\u2019 new neighbor Booth Wilkes-John, Oliver brings his impeccably clipped comic timing...|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150831190734/http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/simpsons-pay-pal-204525|archive-date=31 August 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> in the [[The Simpsons (season 25)|25th season]] episode \"[[Pay Pal (The Simpsons)|Pay Pal]]\", of the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]] animated television series ''[[The Simpsons]]''.\n\n===Film===\nIn 2008, Oliver was given his first film role, playing Dick Pants in ''[[The Love Guru]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2007/09/05/5749/olivers_movie_break | title=Oliver's movie break | publisher=Chortle.co.uk | date=5 September 2007 | access-date=23 May 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090531021752/http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2007/09/05/5749/olivers_movie_break | archive-date=31 May 2009 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> He later voiced Vanity Smurf in ''[[The Smurfs (film)|The Smurfs]]'' film and its [[The Smurfs 2|sequel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2010/04/28/smurfs-john-oliver-snl/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100501120840/http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2010/04/28/smurfs-john-oliver-snl/ |url-status=dead |archive-date= 1 May 2010 |title=Smurfs casting update: 'SNL' cast and John Oliver join voice cast |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=28 April 2010 |access-date=3 May 2010 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.sidereel.com/posts/113913-news-smurfs-casting-update-snl-cast-members-and-john-oliver-join-voice-cast Smurfs casting update, SNL cast members and John Oliver join voice cast] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117023653/http://www.sidereel.com/posts/113913-news-smurfs-casting-update-snl-cast-members-and-john-oliver-join-voice-cast |date=17 November 2015 }} Sidereel 2010</ref> He was originally cast in 2010 to star in the [[Terry Jones]] film ''[[Absolutely Anything]]'' as Neil Clarke,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/John-Oliver-Star-Absolutely-Anything-Robin-Williams-Monty-Python-Cast-Talks-20648.html|title=John Oliver To Star In Absolutely Anything, Robin Williams And Monty Python Cast In Talks|date=14 September 2010|work=CINEMABLEND|access-date=25 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625075127/https://www.cinemablend.com/new/John-Oliver-Star-Absolutely-Anything-Robin-Williams-Monty-Python-Cast-Talks-20648.html|archive-date=25 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> but scheduling conflicts due to the debut of ''[[Last Week Tonight with John Oliver|Last Week Tonight]]'' in 2014 led to the role being recast for [[Simon Pegg]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/simon-pegg-joins-monty-python-members-in-absolutely-anything/|title=Simon Pegg Joins Monty Python Members in 'Absolutely Anything' \u2013 /Film|date=11 December 2013|work=/Film|access-date=25 June 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625050149/http://www.slashfilm.com/simon-pegg-joins-monty-python-members-in-absolutely-anything/|archive-date=25 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, Oliver voiced porcupine Steve in the CGI animation ''[[Wonder Park]]'' and hornbill [[List of The Lion King characters#Zazu|Zazu]] in the [[The Lion King (2019 film)|remake]] of Disney's ''The Lion King''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Donnelly|first1=Matt|title=John Oliver Joins Disney's Live-Action 'The Lion King' (Exclusive)|url=http://www.thewrap.com/john-oliver-joins-live-action-lion-king-zazu-bird-exclusive/|website=The Wraps|accessdate=10 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710230308/http://www.thewrap.com/john-oliver-joins-live-action-lion-king-zazu-bird-exclusive/|archive-date=10 July 2017|url-status=live|date=10 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Other work===\nOliver wrote and presented a [[BBC America]] campaign to have viewers use [[closed captioning]] ([[subtitles]]). Shown in brief segments before shows, \"The following program contains accents you would have heard a lot more if you hadn't [[Boston Tea Party|thrown our tea into Boston Harbour]],\" says one. \"Not even British people can follow the British accent 100 per cent of the time. Therefore you, like me, might want to use closed-captioning.\" Oliver used some of these jokes in his stand-up routine.<ref name=\"Lafayette\">{{cite journal |last1=Lafayette |first1=Jon |title=Translated From the British |journal=Television Week |date=21 May 2007 |volume=26 |issue=21 |page=2 |url=http://www.tvweek.com/blogs/blink/2007/05/translated_from_the_british.php|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080321131957/http://www.tvweek.com/blogs/blink/2007/05/translated_from_the_british.php |archivedate=21 March 2008|accessdate=18 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nOliver frequently appeared on the [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] sports show ''[[Fighting Talk]]''.\n\nFrom 2002 to 2003, Oliver worked on the [[BBC Three|BBC 3]] comedy series ''The State We're In'', along with [[Anita Rani]], [[Jon Holmes]], and [[Robin Ince]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/the_state_were_in/2909905.stm|title=Meet the team|date=8 April 2003|access-date=25 June 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625051619/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/the_state_were_in/2909905.stm|archive-date=25 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Oliver manned the \"results desk\" on an election night episode of [[Armando Iannucci]]'s satirical show ''[[Gash (TV series)|Gash]]'' on [[Channel 4]]. He would work with Iannucci again in 2005, as a panellist in the second episode of ''[[Armando Iannucci's Charm Offensive]]''.\n\nIn 2004, Oliver wrote and performed in the satirical radio program ''[[The Department]]'' on [[BBC Radio 4]], with frequent comedy partner [[Andy Zaltzman]] and [[Chris Addison]]. He portrayed the character Victor Gooch for all three series, prior to the cancellation of the program in 2006.\n\nOliver performed various roles in the 2009 [[Comedy Central]] series ''[[Important Things with Demetri Martin]]''.\n\nIn 2009, Oliver made a cameo appearance as the actor [[Rip Torn]] in the music video for [[the Fiery Furnaces]] single \"Even in the Rain\", which is based on the story of the making of the film ''[[Easy Rider]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/37279-video-premiere-the-fiery-furnaces-even-in-the-rain/|title=Video Premiere: The Fiery Furnaces: 'Even in the Rain'|website=pitchfork.com|publisher=Pitchfork Media|date=3 December 2009|access-date=7 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107021152/http://pitchfork.com/news/37279-video-premiere-the-fiery-furnaces-even-in-the-rain/|archive-date=7 January 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Oliver began working as an executive producer for ''[[Wyatt Cenac\u2019s Problem Areas]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/wyatt-cenac-star-john-oliver-docu-series-hbo-169395|title=Wyatt Cenac to Star in John Oliver Docu-Series on HBO|work=Broadcasting & Cable|access-date=24 June 2018|language=en-us|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624093004/https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/wyatt-cenac-star-john-oliver-docu-series-hbo-169395|archive-date=24 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Influence and the \"John Oliver effect\"==\n[[File:John Oliver 1.jpg|thumb|upright|Oliver speaking at the 2014 [[Crunchies]]]]\nOliver has said that among his comedic influences are: [[Armando Iannucci]], [[David Letterman]], [[Monty Python]], [[Peter Cook]], [[Richard Pryor]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/gallery/john-oliver-reveals-his-5-696662|title=HBO's New Late-Night Host John Oliver Reveals His 5 Comedic Influences|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=16 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418164057/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/gallery/john-oliver-reveals-his-5-696662|archive-date=18 April 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Jon Stewart]].<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/comedy/comedy-news/11546015/How-John-Oliver-became-an-American-star.html |title=How John Oliver became an American star |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=17 April 2015 |location= London |date=17 April 2015}}</ref> On Monty Python he states, \"citing them as an influence is almost redundant. It\u2019s assumed. I saw ''[[Monty Python's Life of Brian|Life of Brian]]'' in middle school, when a substitute teacher put it on to keep us quiet on a rainy day. I\u2019m not sure he knew exactly what he was showing us, but I\u2019ve always been hugely grateful for the reckless professional mistake he made that day, because I\u2019ve never forgotten how it made me feel.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=John Oliver on Monty Python: 'inspirational idiots who changed comedy' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/jan/07/john-oliver-monty-python-inspirational-idiots-who-changed-comedy |accessdate=25 August 2019 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nOliver's comedic commentary has been credited with helping influence US legislation, regulations, court rulings, and other aspects of US culture; this influence has been dubbed \"The John Oliver effect\".<ref name=\"time.com\"/><ref name=\"Dekel\"/> This came from [[Net Neutrality (Last Week Tonight)#\"Net Neutrality\"|the show's fifth episode]], which dealt with [[net neutrality]], a subject that had previously been considered obscure and technical.<ref name=transform>{{cite web|last1=Brody|first1=Ben|title=How John Oliver Transformed the Net Neutrality Debate Once and for All|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2015-02-26/how-john-oliver-transformed-the-net-neutrality-debate-once-and-for-all|website=Bloomberg|access-date=27 August 2015|date=26 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150814011603/http://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2015-02-26/how-john-oliver-transformed-the-net-neutrality-debate-once-and-for-all|archive-date=14 August 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Oliver documented problems attributed to internet service providers and argued that the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) could resolve these concerns with upcoming changes to internet regulation. Oliver then encouraged viewers to submit public comments through the FCC's website. The FCC's website promptly crashed.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roppolo|first1=Michael|title=John Oliver's rant about net neutrality crashes FCC site|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/fcc-comment-page-crashes-after-john-olivers-rant-about-net-neutrality/|website=CBS News|access-date=27 August 2015|date=3 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150815023746/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/fcc-comment-page-crashes-after-john-olivers-rant-about-net-neutrality/|archive-date=15 August 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Internal FCC emails revealed the clip was being watched inside the agency.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lecher|first1=Colin|title=Read the FCC's internal emails about John Oliver's net neutrality segment|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/11/13/7205817/fcc-john-oliver-net-neutrality-emails|website=The Verge|access-date=27 August 2015|date=13 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821115920/http://www.theverge.com/2014/11/13/7205817/fcc-john-oliver-net-neutrality-emails|archive-date=21 August 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> FCC Chairman [[Tom Wheeler]] publicly addressed the video.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tom|last=Risen|title=FCC Chairman Tom Wheeler: 'I Am Not a Dingo'|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/blogs/washington-whispers/2014/06/13/fcc-chairman-tom-wheeler-i-am-not-a-dingo|website=U.S. News & World Report|access-date=27 August 2015|date=13 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117024329/http://www.usnews.com/news/blogs/washington-whispers/2014/06/13/fcc-chairman-tom-wheeler-i-am-not-a-dingo|archive-date=17 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The FCC was flooded with 3.7 million comments on the subject, by far the most for any issue in the agency's history.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kastrenakes|first1=Jacob|title=FCC received a total of 3.7 million comments on net neutrality|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/9/16/6257887/fcc-net-neutrality-3-7-million-comments-made|website=The Verge|access-date=27 August 2015|date=16 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905160733/http://www.theverge.com/2014/9/16/6257887/fcc-net-neutrality-3-7-million-comments-made|archive-date=5 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Reporters detected a shift in the FCC's stance: Before Oliver's segment, ''[[The New York Times]]'' described an FCC proposal that would leave net neutrality \"all but dead,\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wyatt|first1=Edward|title=F.C.C., in a Shift, Backs Fast Lanes for Web Traffic|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/24/technology/fcc-new-net-neutrality-rules.html|website=The New York Times|access-date=28 August 2015|date=23 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701015851/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/24/technology/fcc-new-net-neutrality-rules.html|archive-date=1 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> but the paper later said that chairman Wheeler showed \"a steady shift toward stronger regulation.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Steve|last=Lohr|title=F.C.C. Plans Strong Hand to Regulate the Internet|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/05/technology/fcc-wheeler-net-neutrality.html|website=The New York Times|access-date=28 August 2015|date=4 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906105247/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/05/technology/fcc-wheeler-net-neutrality.html|archive-date=6 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Ultimately, the FCC enacted robust net neutrality rules that classified broadband internet service as a public utility.<ref>{{cite news|first1= Rebecca R.|last1= Ruiz|first2= Steve|last2= Lohr|title= F.C.C. Approves Net Neutrality Rules, Classifying Broadband Internet Service as a Utility|website= NYTimes.com|publisher= The New York Times|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/27/technology/net-neutrality-fcc-vote-internet-utility.html|date= 26 February 2015|access-date= 27 February 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150226212654/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/27/technology/net-neutrality-fcc-vote-internet-utility.html|archive-date= 26 February 2015|url-status= live|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Oliver was credited with transforming the net neutrality debate.<ref name=transform />\n\nA [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|Ninth Circuit Court]] judge cited a ''Last Week Tonight'' segment about the lesser constitutional rights of residents of [[United States territory|US territories]] in a ruling in favour of the residents of [[Guam]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rubino|first1=Kathryn|title=The Ninth Circuit Hearts John Oliver|url=http://abovethelaw.com/2015/08/the-ninth-circuit-hearts-john-oliver/|website=Above The Law|access-date=28 August 2015|date=27 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=9th Cir. Rips Guam for Keeping Tax Refunds|url=http://www.courthousenews.com/2015/08/26/9th-cir-rips-guam-for-keeping-tax-refunds.htm|website=Courthouse News Service|access-date=28 August 2015|date=26 August 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150830013143/http://www.courthousenews.com/2015/08/26/9th-cir-rips-guam-for-keeping-tax-refunds.htm|archivedate=30 August 2015}}</ref>{{efn|See: {{cite web|title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver: U.S. Territories (HBO)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CesHr99ezWE| website= YouTube.com| access-date=28 August 2015|date=8 March 2015}}}} Members of [[United States Congress|Congress]] credited Oliver with helping win a vote to enforce protections for chicken farmers who speak out about industry practices after a ''Last Week Tonight'' segment aired on the subject.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Capriel|first1=Jonathan A.|title=Comedian influences Ag Bill, members of Congress say|url=http://www.shfwire.com/comedian-influences-ag-bill-members-congress-say/|website=Scripps Howard Foundation Wire|access-date=28 August 2015|date=19 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816004523/http://www.shfwire.com/comedian-influences-ag-bill-members-congress-say/|archive-date=16 August 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ag spending bill contains big win to protect rights for chicken farmers after viral John Oliver video brought attention to their plight|url=https://pingree.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/ag-spending-bill-contains-big-win-protect-rights-chicken-farmers-after|website=Congresswoman Chellie Pingree, 1st District of Maine|publisher=United States House of Representatives|access-date=28 August 2015|date=18 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908031214/https://pingree.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/ag-spending-bill-contains-big-win-protect-rights-chicken-farmers-after|archive-date=8 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>{{efn|See: {{cite web|title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver: Chickens (HBO)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X9wHzt6gBgI| website= YouTube.com| access-date=28 August 2015|date=17 May 2015}}}} A [[Washington, D.C.]] council member proposed a resolution in Oliver's honour after he aired a segment on the district's [[District of Columbia statehood movement|struggle to attain statehood]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The John Oliver Effect|first=Andrew|last=Giambrone|url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/blogs/citydesk/2015/08/05/the-john-oliver-effect/|website=WashingtonCityPaper.com|access-date=28 August 2015|date=5 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910045014/http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/blogs/citydesk/2015/08/05/the-john-oliver-effect/|archive-date=10 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>{{efn|See: {{cite web|title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver: Washington DC Statehood (HBO)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4Z4j2CrJRn4|website=YouTube|access-date=28 August 2015|date=2 August 2015}}}}\n\nOliver maintains that he is not a journalist,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Robinson|first1=Joanna|title=John Oliver Rejects the Notion That He's a Respected Journalist|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/05/john-oliver-not-a-journalist|website=Vanity Fair|access-date=28 August 2015|date=13 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909075740/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/05/john-oliver-not-a-journalist|archive-date=9 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> but reporters have argued that his show does engage in journalism.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Suebsaeng|first1=Asawin|title='Last Week Tonight' Does Real Journalism, No Matter What John Oliver Says|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/09/29/last-week-tonight-does-real-journalism-no-matter-what-john-oliver-says.html|newspaper=The Daily Beast|access-date=28 August 2015|date=29 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150901034813/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/09/29/last-week-tonight-does-real-journalism-no-matter-what-john-oliver-says.html|archive-date=1 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=David|first1=Bauder|title=Oliver adds journalism to his comedy|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/ea1d53d73d0e4a199b65d19181660e9e/oliver-adds-journalism-his-comedy|website=Associated Press|access-date=28 August 2015|date=26 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150704065656/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/ea1d53d73d0e4a199b65d19181660e9e/oliver-adds-journalism-his-comedy|archive-date=4 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Poniewozik|first1=James|title=Unfortunately, John Oliver, You Are a Journalist|url=http://time.com/3589285/unfortunately-john-oliver-you-are-a-journalist/|website=TIME|access-date=28 August 2015|date=17 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725193947/http://time.com/3589285/unfortunately-john-oliver-you-are-a-journalist/|archive-date=25 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Peabody Award]]s honoured Oliver, saying his program engages in \"investigative reports that 'real' news programs would do well to emulate\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Collins|first1=Scott|title=Peabody Awards go to John Oliver, Amy Schumer, 'Jane the Virgin'|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-peabody-awards-john-oliver-amy-schumer-fargo-20150416-story.html|website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=28 August 2015|date=16 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010190536/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-peabody-awards-john-oliver-amy-schumer-fargo-20150416-story.html|archive-date=10 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> One example of Oliver's investigative work is a segment on The [[Miss America]] Organization, which bills itself as \"the world's largest provider of scholarships for women.\"<ref name=citypages>{{cite web|last1=Rupar|first1=Aaron|title=John Oliver's Devastating Takedown of Miss America Has a Local Angle|url=http://www.citypages.com/news/john-olivers-devastating-takedown-of-miss-america-has-a-local-angle-video-6533952|website=City Pages|access-date=28 August 2015|date=24 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150829084844/http://www.citypages.com/news/john-olivers-devastating-takedown-of-miss-america-has-a-local-angle-video-6533952|archive-date=29 August 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Oliver's team, which includes four researchers with journalism backgrounds,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Blake|first1=Meredith|title=Seven things we learned at breakfast with John Oliver|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-john-oliver-last-week-tonight-season-2-20150204-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=28 August 2015|date=4 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926194527/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-john-oliver-last-week-tonight-season-2-20150204-story.html|archive-date=26 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> collected and analysed the organization's state and federal tax forms to find that the organization's scholarship program only distributes a small fraction of its claimed \"$45 million made available annually\".<ref>{{cite web| last1= Chung| first1= Jen| title= Video: John Oliver Shreds Miss America's Claim To Be \"Leading Provider\" Of Scholarships To Women| url= http://gothamist.com/2014/09/22/john_oliver_miss_america.php| website= Gothamist| access-date= 28 August 2015| date= 22 September 2014| url-status= dead| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150510013519/http://gothamist.com/2014/09/22/john_oliver_miss_america.php| archivedate= 10 May 2015| df= dmy-all}}</ref> Oliver said that at the national level, the Miss America Organization and Miss America Foundation together spent only $482,000 in cash scholarships in 2012.<ref name=citypages /> Oliver found that at the state level, The [[Miss Alabama]] Pageant claimed that it had provided $2,592,000 in scholarships to [[Troy University]] despite not actually distributing any such scholarships.<ref>{{cite web| last1= Herman| first1= Barbara| title= John Oliver Takes On Miss America Pageant's 'Unbelievable' Scholarship Claims| url= http://www.ibtimes.com/john-oliver-takes-miss-america-pageants-unbelievable-scholarship-claims-1692908| work= International Business Times| access-date= 28 August 2015| date= 22 September 2014| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150912191525/http://www.ibtimes.com/john-oliver-takes-miss-america-pageants-unbelievable-scholarship-claims-1692908| archive-date= 12 September 2015| url-status= live| df= dmy-all}}</ref> The official YouTube video of Oliver's Miss America segment has been viewed more than 15 million times.<ref>{{cite web|title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver: Miss America Pageant (HBO)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oDPCmmZifE8|website=YouTube|access-date=28 August 2015|date=21 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150829084847/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oDPCmmZifE8|archive-date=29 August 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Society of Women Engineers]] said Oliver's mention of their scholarship in his story led to $25,000 in donations in the first two days after the episode.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gregory|first1=Ted|title='John Oliver bounce' benefits Chicago-based women's engineering group|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/tv/ct-pageant-engineer-scholarships-20140923-story.html|website=Chicago Tribune|access-date=28 August 2015|date=24 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150828031315/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/tv/ct-pageant-engineer-scholarships-20140923-story.html|archive-date=28 August 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOliver has also founded and legally incorporated a church, [[Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption]], to demonstrate how easy it is to qualify as a church and receive tax exempt status in the United States.<ref>{{cite news | last1= Respers France | first1= Lisa | title= John Oliver forms his own church and just keeps on winning | website= CNN.com | url= http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/17/entertainment/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-feat/ | access-date= 28 August 2015 | date= 17 August 2015 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150820033420/http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/17/entertainment/john-oliver-last-week-tonight-feat/ | archive-date= 20 August 2015 | url-status= live | df= dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=John Oliver's Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption Church|url=http://www.ourladyofperpetualexemption.com/|website=Our Lady of Perpetual Exemption|access-date=28 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150827212918/http://www.ourladyofperpetualexemption.com/|archive-date=27 August 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The church was created in conjunction with a segment on televangelists who have tax-free mansions and private jets funded by millions of dollars in donations, which are sent in the belief that money given to televangelists can result in God rewarding donors with money, blessings, and cured diseases.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Oliver Starts His Own Church to Expose \"Predatory\" Televangelists|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-exposes-televangelists-by-815767|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=28 August 2015|date=17 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821010006/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-exposes-televangelists-by-815767|archive-date=21 August 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>{{efn|See: {{cite web|title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver: Televangelists (HBO)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7y1xJAVZxXg|website=YouTube|access-date=28 August 2015|date=16 August 2015}}}} The next week, Oliver showed off the large quantity of unsolicited donations mailed to him.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mandle|first1=Chris|title=John Oliver inundated with donations after setting up fake church to make a point about tax-dodging televangelists|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/john-oliver-inundated-with-donations-after-setting-up-fake-church-to-make-a-point-about-taxdodging-televangelists-10469577.html|website=The Independent|access-date=28 August 2015|date=24 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150828003157/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/john-oliver-inundated-with-donations-after-setting-up-fake-church-to-make-a-point-about-taxdodging-televangelists-10469577.html|archive-date=28 August 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Update on Pastor John Oliver's Church|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mUndxpbufkg|website=YouTube|access-date=28 August 2015|date=24 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004064803/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mUndxpbufkg|archive-date=4 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The church's website stated that donations would go to [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res|Doctors Without Borders]] upon the church's dissolution.<ref>{{cite web|title=Donate Now!| url=http://www.ourladyofperpetualexemption.com/donate.html|website=OurLadyofPerpetualExemption.com|access-date=30 August 2015| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150905112831/http://www.ourladyofperpetualexemption.com/donate.html| archivedate=5 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nOliver's [[Donald Trump (Last Week Tonight)|February 2016 segment]] on presidential candidate [[Donald Trump]] received over 85 million views on Facebook and YouTube within a month, and was reportedly the \"most watched piece of HBO content ever\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ryan|first1=Shane|title=John Oliver's \"Donald Drumpf\" Segment Broke Every HBO Viewing Record|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2016/03/john-olivers-donald-drumpf-segment-broke-every-hbo.html|website=Paste Magazine|access-date=31 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401165346/http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2016/03/john-olivers-donald-drumpf-segment-broke-every-hbo.html|archive-date=1 April 2016|url-status=live|date=30 March 2016}}</ref> A network spokesperson said on the piece, \"this is a record for any piece of HBO content\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stelter|first1=Brian|title=Even John Oliver enjoys a Drumpf bump|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/03/30/media/john-oliver-donald-trump/index.html|website=CNNMoney|access-date=31 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331201056/http://money.cnn.com/2016/03/30/media/john-oliver-donald-trump/index.html|archive-date=31 March 2016|url-status=live|date=30 March 2016}}</ref> In 2018 on Last Week Tonight, Oliver presented [[A Day in the Life of Marlon Bundo]], a gay parody of [[Marlon Bundo's A Day in the Life of the Vice President]] with [[Marlon Bundo#Children's_books|Marlon Bundo]] as protagonist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://amp.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/mar/22/john-oliver-gay-rabbit-book-parody-outsells-mike-pence-original-amazon|title=John Oliver's gay rabbit book parody outsells Mike Pence's original on Amazon|date=22 March 2018|work=the Guardian|access-date=22 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322073829/https://amp.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/mar/22/john-oliver-gay-rabbit-book-parody-outsells-mike-pence-original-amazon|archive-date=22 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:John Oliver and Kate Norley (31202364806) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Oliver and Norley in 2016]]\nOliver lives in [[New York City]] with his wife Kate Norley, an [[Iraq War]] veteran who served as a [[United States Army]] [[medic]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Slonim |first=Jeffrey |url=https://people.com/celebrity/the-daily-shows-john-oliver-is-engaged/ |title=''The Daily Show''{{'}}s John Oliver Is Engaged |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=3 October 2010 |accessdate=13 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213124012/https://people.com/celebrity/the-daily-shows-john-oliver-is-engaged/ |archive-date=13 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Oliver has said that they met at the [[2008 Republican National Convention]]; he was doing a piece for ''The Daily Show'' and Norley was campaigning with [[Vets for Freedom]]. She and other veterans hid Oliver, the other correspondents, and the camera crew from security.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://jumbodump.com/2009/06/03/john-oliver-radio-interview-3/| title=John Oliver Radio Interview| date=3 June 2009| access-date=30 November 2009| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091210150058/http://jumbodump.com/2009/06/03/john-oliver-radio-interview-3/| archive-date=10 December 2009| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=John Oliver Interview part 1| url=http://www.latenightwithjimmyfallon.com/video/john-oliver-part-1/n26467/| work=[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]| date=22 August 2012| access-date=24 August 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130224033559/http://www.latenightwithjimmyfallon.com/video/john-oliver-part-1/n26467/| archive-date=24 February 2013| url-status=live| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The two married in October 2011.<ref name=biography.com /> Together, the couple have two sons, one born prematurely<ref>{{cite web|last1=Oliver|first1=John|title=Last Week Tonight with John Oliver- 106|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7VG_s2PCH_c|website=Youtube.com|publisher=HBO|accessdate=26 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626070107/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7VG_s2PCH_c|archive-date=26 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> in 2015<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.eonline.com/news/715221/john-oliver-and-wife-kate-norley-welcome-a-baby-boy| title=John Oliver and Wife Kate Norley Welcome a Baby Boy| first=Francesca| last=Bacardi| publisher=[[E! News]]| date=12 November 2015| access-date=12 November 2015| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151122083948/http://www.eonline.com/news/715221/john-oliver-and-wife-kate-norley-welcome-a-baby-boy| archive-date=22 November 2015| url-status=live| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-baby-news-last-839887|title=John Oliver Baby News: 'Last Week Tonight' Host, Wife Welcome Son|first=Hilary|last=Lewis|date=12 November 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=15 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151115005355/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-oliver-baby-news-last-839887|archive-date=15 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and one born in 2018.<ref name=\"People2018\">{{cite web |last1=Juneau |first1=Jen |last2=Fecteau |first2=Jessica |title=Emmy Winner John Oliver Reveals He and Wife Kate Welcomed Their Second Child Three Months Ago |url=https://people.com/parents/emmys-2018-john-oliver-welcomes-second-child-son-wife-kate/ |website=People |accessdate=19 September 2018 |date=19 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919183104/https://people.com/parents/emmys-2018-john-oliver-welcomes-second-child-son-wife-kate/ |archive-date=19 September 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Oliver occasionally wears a [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|1st Cavalry Division]] lapel pin \u2013 his wife's unit in Iraq.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://military.id.me/community-news/watch-john-oliver-brag-about-a-united-states-army-vet/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=10 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210152600/https://military.id.me/community-news/watch-john-oliver-brag-about-a-united-states-army-vet/ |archive-date=10 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He has a younger sister who lives in Australia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/last-week-tonight-host-john-olivers-fascination-with-tony-abbott-john-howard-tim-fischer-20150308-13wylf.html|title=Last Week Tonight host John Oliver's fascination with Tony Abbott, John Howard, Tim Fischer|last=Cummings|first=Pip|date=6 March 2015|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=December 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOliver's immigration status placed certain constraints on what he could do in his adopted country, but also provided him with comedy material as he poked fun at the opacity and occasional absurdity of the process of obtaining [[Permanent residence (United States)|US residency]]. Oliver was one of the many writers on the [[Picketing (protest)|picket lines]] during the [[2007\u20132008 Writers Guild of America strike|Writers' Guild strike]], which brought ''The Daily Show'' to a halt;<ref>{{cite web | url=http://gothamist.com/2007/11/15/john_oliver_wri.php | title=John Oliver, writer | date=15 October 2007 | publisher=Gothamist.com | access-date=19 April 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080420091836/http://gothamist.com/2007/11/15/john_oliver_wri.php | archivedate=20 April 2008 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> he appeared on the show upon its resuming production on 7 January 2008. During a sketch, he pointed out that he was then in America on a [[Visa (document)|visitors' visa]] that requires him not to strike while the show is in production, as violation of the terms of the visa would be grounds for deportation.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cc.com/video-clips/ixq99m/the-daily-show-with-jon-stewart-olivers-on-the-strike| title=Olivers on the Strike| date=12 November 2015| access-date=8 January 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001034405/http://www.cc.com/video-clips/ixq99m/the-daily-show-with-jon-stewart-olivers-on-the-strike| archive-date=1 October 2015| url-status=live| df=dmy-all}}</ref> When asked about his residency status in early 2009, Oliver said, \"It's an ongoing, and slightly unsettling, battle to be honest. I tried engraving 'Give me your tired, your poor, and your aspiring comic performers' into the base of the [[Statue of Liberty]], but apparently that's not legally binding.\"<ref name=\"Comic Crumpet\">{{cite web |url = http://suicidegirls.com/interviews/John+Oliver%3A+Comic+Crumpet/ |title = John Oliver: Comic Crumpet |publisher = [[SuicideGirls.com]] |date = 13 January 2009 |access-date = 14 January 2009 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090117033929/http://suicidegirls.com/interviews/John+Oliver%3A+Comic+Crumpet/ |archive-date = 17 January 2009 |url-status = live |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn an episode of ''[[The Bugle]]'' released 2 November 2009, and recorded on 30 October 2009, Oliver announced he \"finally got approved for [his] [[United States Permanent Resident Card|green card]]\" (for US residency), noting that now he can \"get arrested filming bits for ''[[The Daily Show]]''\".<ref name=\"Bugle 94\">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/us_and_americas/us_elections/the_bugle/article6895545.ece |title=The Bugle #94: Does the EU really want El Presidente Blair? |date=31 October 2009 |work=[[The Times]] |access-date=31 October 2009 |location=London |first=Tom |last=Wright |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605002109/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/us_and_americas/us_elections/the_bugle/article6895545.ece |archive-date=5 June 2011 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Oliver says he was given a scare when applying at the [[Embassy of the United States, London|United States embassy in London]], when an immigration officer asked, \"Give me one good reason I should let you back in to insult my country,\" which the officer followed up with, \"Oh, I'm just kidding, I love the show.\" Since then, he has referred to Americans as \"us\" or \"you\" based on what each segment has demanded.<ref>{{cite web|last=Burkeman|first=Oliver|title=John Oliver: a very British coup|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2013/jun/07/john-oliver-the-daily-show|work=The Guardian|access-date=1 September 2013|date=7 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131115111618/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2013/jun/07/john-oliver-the-daily-show|archive-date=15 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Oliver became a US citizen on 13 December 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/watch-america-john-oliver-is-officially-a-us-citizen-now-1273984|title=Watch Out, America: John Oliver Is Officially a U.S. Citizen Now|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\nOliver's philanthropy includes an on-air giveaway in which he forgave over $15&nbsp;million of medical debt owed by over 9,000 people. He purchased the debt for $60,000 and forgave it on his show of 4 June in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Salzillo|first1=Leslie|date=6 June 2016|website=Daily Kos|url=https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2016/6/6/1535091/-John-Oliver-buys-up-15-million-in-medical-debt-then-pays-off-the-debt-for-9-000-people-in-hardship|title=John Oliver buys up $15 million in medical debt, then pays off the debt for 9,000 people in hardship|access-date=11 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212084254/https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2016/6/6/1535091/-John-Oliver-buys-up-15-million-in-medical-debt-then-pays-off-the-debt-for-9-000-people-in-hardship|archive-date=12 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSince moving to the United States, Oliver has been a fan of the [[New York Mets]].<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OwlPnYgc9eM</ref> Oliver has said that being a [[New York Yankees]] fan would be the \"wrong thing to do morally.\"<ref>https://elitesportsny.com/2019/05/27/john-oliver-on-rooting-for-new-york-yankees-wrong-thing-to-do-morally/</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[The Love Guru]]''\n| Dick Pants\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2011\n| ''Moves: The Rise and Rise of the New Pornographers''\n| Protest Leader\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''{{sortname|The|Smurfs|The Smurfs (film)}}''\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Vanity Smurf]] (voice)\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2013\n| ''[[The Smurfs 2]]''\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Smurfs: The Legend of Smurfy Hollow]]''\n| Short film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2019\n|''[[Wonder Park]]''\n| Steve (voice)\n| \n|-\n| ''[[The Lion King (2019 film)|The Lion King]]''\n| [[List of The Lion King characters#Zazu|Zazu]] (voice)\n| \n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Bleak House (1985 TV serial)|Bleak House]]'